            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>YMYL stands for "Your Money or Your Life." It's a term from Google's Search Quality Rater Guidelines used to describe content topics where incorrect information could seriously harm users — including medical advice, financial guidance, legal information, and safety instructions.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Why does YMYL matter for SEO?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Google holds YMYL pages to the highest E-E-A-T (Experience, Expertise, Authoritativeness, Trustworthiness) standards. Content on YMYL topics written by unqualified authors, lacking citations, or making unverifiable claims is likely to be rated low quality by human reviewers — which can inform algorithmic ranking decisions.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do I know if my content is YMYL?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Ask: if this information were wrong or misleading, could it cause serious harm to a real person? If the answer is yes — medical, financial, legal, safety, or news content — it's YMYL. The test isn't the topic itself but the potential impact of getting it wrong.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can small websites rank for YMYL topics?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes, but it requires demonstrable expertise. Small sites can rank for YMYL queries if their authors have real credentials, content is rigorously researched and cited, and the overall website demonstrates trustworthiness. A solo physician's blog about patient health can outrank a large generic health site with no expert authors.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is YMYL a direct ranking factor?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>YMYL is not a direct algorithmic ranking signal — it's a categorisation framework used by Google's human quality raters. However, quality ratings do inform machine learning systems that shape ranking. In practice, YMYL topics face stricter quality thresholds, and weak E-E-A-T on YMYL content correlates strongly with poor rankings.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

